The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Troubled Tours
                                                                                                                                                                                                     Troubled Tours
                            
	 Nov. 1984: Indias tour of Pakistan is cut short during the Sialkot ODI on account of concerns over security after Indira Gandhis assassination.         
	 April 1987: New Zealand return home after an explosion following the first Test against Sri Lanka in Colombo.         
	 Nov. 1992: The New Zealand tour of Sri Lanka was close to being abandoned when a suicide bomb attack left five dead outside their Colombo hotel. Five players accepted the New Zealand boards offer to return home and the tour was restructured with two Tests instead of three!         
	 May 2002: New Zealand cancelled the rest of their tour of Pakistan following a suicide bomb attack outside the team hotel in Karachi.         
	 Aug. 2006: A few of the tri-series matches between hosts Sri Lanka, India and South Africa were initially washed out because of rain. Then the tournament had to be abandoned when the South African team returned home citing security reasons as a bomb had gone off in Colombo.         
	 Nov. 2008: England decided not to play the last two ODIs during their tour of India because of the terrorist attacks in Mumbai.           COMPILED BY MOHANDAS MENON                                                                                                                      
